context: There are many Hokkien speakers among overseas Chinese in Southeast Asia as well as in the United States. Many <b14_0>ethnic <a0_0>Han Chinese emigrants<b14_0/><a0_0/> to the region were <b11_0>Hoklo from southern Fujian<b11_0/>, and brought the language to what is now <a1_0>Burma<a1_0/> (<b6_0>Myanmar<b6_0/>), <b5_0>Indonesia<b5_0/> (the former <a2_0>Dutch East Indies<a2_0/>) and present day Malaysia and Singapore (formerly Malaya and the British Straits Settlements). <b13_0>Many of the Hokkien dialects of this region<b13_0/> are highly similar to Taiwanese and Amoy. Hokkien is reportedly the native language of <b12_0>up to <a3_0>98.5%<b12_0/><a3_0/> of the Chinese Filipino in the Philippines, among which is known locally as <a4_0>Lan-nang or Lán-lâng-oē<a4_0/> ("<b9_0>Our people’s language<b9_0/>"). <b7_0><b8_0><b10_0>Hokkien<b7_0/> speakers<b10_0/><b8_0/> form the largest group of Chinese in Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia.[citation needed]
